at impressionism was the first art historical movement to embrace such changes. Looking principally at Claude Monet, Camille Pissarro, Alfred Sisley, Armand Guillaumin, and Gustave Caillebotte, Rubin has selected works in four categories: industrial waterways, trains, factories, and photographic viewpoints in the modern city. The examples convey not only these major themes but also the painters' belief in the progress of civilization through science and industry. The book thus expands the scope of impressionist celebrations of modernity to include "impressionism's other landscape."  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns in art. 0aImpressionism (Art)zFrance. 0aIndustrialization in art. 4aArt. 4aEuropean. 7aART / European.2bisacsh1 aRubin, James H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024801440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093295140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932951423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932951/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles